{ Black is clearly losing here. White has almost all of the advantages in the position: two extra pawns, connected including the passed f pawn. Our king is cut off as well, while white's pieces are active with several immediate threats (e.g., winning the h pawn). However, applying good endgame principles we can at least try to make it difficult. First up, where to move the rook which is under attack. Remember that piece activity is critical, so we are better off attacking one of white's backward pawns rather than defending the h pawn. } { [%csl Gh3,Gb2] }
30... Re1+ 31. Kf2 Rh1 { Threatening both the h pawn and Rh2+ Kg3 Rxb2 } 32. f5?! { White rushes to push the f pawn, but is too hasty. Improve the king first! Kg3 would have defended against both threats while bringing the king closer to the action. } 32... Rxh3 33. f6?? { Trying to push the passed pawn, but now the weak king allows a solution. } 33... Rf3+! 34. Ke2 Rxf6 35. Bf5 { Material is now equal. However, white still has more active pieces, which means white is the one pressing for a win. Which piece do we improve first? Clearly the most important one -- the king! But the king is cut off by the rook on a7. So, we'll need to give it some cover to break free. } 35... Rf7!? { This lets our king break free, but comes at a major cost. Typically endgames with the king, pawns, and bishops of the same color tend to be winnable (bishops of the opposite color tend to be drawn). Since white's king and bishop are both better pieces than ours, we might be trading into a losing position. However, we should **know** that if we cannot activate our king, the game is lost, so a position that might be losing is better than one which is certainly losing. } 36. Rxf7 Kxf7 37. Ke3 Kf6 38. Kf4 { First, we had to activate the king. Now, white cannot inflitrate without the pawns. Next, we have a new problem, often described as Capablanca's Rule. A bishop on a light square can attack pawns on light squares but not dark squares. So, eventually white will be able to use the bishop to create weaknesses that we must defend. For example, if white plays Bd7, we will have to defend c6, and if we push the pawn instead, it is the pawn that falls. We want our pawns to be ones on light squares! } { [%cal Gf5d7] } 38... Bb3 39. Be4 { If Bd7, we would have to come back to d5. Instead, white chooses the other diagonal to attack our c pawn. But now we can find a dark square! } 39... c5 40. Bd3 b4 { Exchanging would still leave our remaining pawns both on dark squares. } 41. c4?! Ba2 42. Be2 Bb3 { Repeating is fine, since we are hoping for a draw. } 43. Ke4 { There is only one move here - see if you can find it. } 43... Ke6! { Keep opposition and stop white's king from getting through! (Chess.com gives this a great move since anything else loses, but it should be easy to find) } { [%csl Gf5,Ge5,Gd5] } 44. Kf4 Ba4 { We can leave the king on e6 because the h pawn helps us to keep white's king out. } { [%csl Gg5,Gf5,Ge5,Gd5] } 45. Bf3 Bd7 46. Bd5+ Kf6 { [%csl Gg5,Gf5,Ge5] } 47. Bf3 Be6 48. Be2 Bf7 { White is now getting stuck. The king cannot infiltrate because our king and bishop work together to create a barrier. White could trade the g/h pawns, but that will not help. } { [%csl Gh5,Gg5,Gf5,Ge5,Gd5] } 49. Bd3 Be6 50. b3 { Note that white's pawns are now the ones on the wrong color. As long as we do not make a mistake and let white's king in, the bishop is harmless and we will hold our draw. In fact, if we could put our bishop someplace like d1, we might even be able to make some offensive threats (although it's hard to see any way it can get there). } 50... Bf7 51. Bf5 { White hopes that we might end up in zugzwang and be forced to let his king in. However, as long as we have a bishop, we should never run out of places to put it, since our bishop no longer has any defensive responsibilities with all our pawns on dark squares. } { [%cal Gf7g8,Gg8f7,Gf7e8,Ge8f7] } 51... Bg8 52. Ke4 { Here is white's plan: we cannot use the king to keep white from reaching d5 anymore, which means we have to keep the bishop on the g8-a2 diagonal. However, because white's king is now on e4 instead of f4, we can now force the draw. } 52... Be6 { Bf7 would have been fine as well. White still cannot get the king any further. However, this is more forcing. Because the king is now on e4, white cannot decline the trade without losing the g pawn, after which black will win. } 53. Bxe6! Kxe6 { And because white's king is on e4, once we recapture on e6, it is white's move, which means we have opposition! } 54. Kf3 { White has one more trick to try. But by now we should know the solution! } 54... Kf7! { [%csl Gf6,Gf5,Gf4] } 55. Kf4 Kf6 $10 { White now recognizes we can use opposition to keep his king out, and a draw was agreed. } { [%csl Gf5] } 1/2-1/2


